==English==

===Etymology===
{{compound|en|cheat|line}}, because the first cheatlines aimed to "cheat the eye", making aircraft appear more streamlined.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|aviation}} In [[civil]] [[aviation]], a [[decorative]] [[horizontal]] [[band]] of [[color]] applied to both sides of an [[aircraft]]'s [[fuselage]] of as part of its [[livery]].

====Usage notes====
Airlines with liveries featuring decades-old cheatline designs include [[w:American Airlines|American Airlines]], [[w:Alitalia|Alitalia]], and [[w:LOT Polish Airlines|LOT Polish Airlines]].

